Adds a new event (KycoRawMessageOutError)

KycoMessageOutError inherits from KycoAppEvent, so it can not be added
into the raw buffer. As it can be generated on the tcp_handler (when
trying to read/recv on the connection), and the tcp_handler can only
access the raw buffer, so I've created the "KycoRawMessageOutError" to
work as a wrapper for KycoMessageOutError.

Adding new KycoExceptions.

* KycoCoreException: For generic exceptions raised on the Controller.
* KycoSwitchOfflineException: Exception used mainly when trying to send
                              data to a switch that is offline

Handling exceptions on KycoSwitch.

Catching OSError and SocketError, disconnecting the switch and raising
these exceptions.
Also, if the 'switch.send' method is called while the switch being
offline (with socket attribute being None), then raises the exception
KycoSwitchOfflineException.

Fix metadata access on setup.py

FIX #316

Previously we were importing the metadata.py module as a python module.
But, by doing so we also call the kytos/core/__init__.py file, that
tries to import kytos.core.controller module and, as a consequence,
lot's of dependencies (such as Flask), that hasn't yet being installed.
So, this is why we need to parse the 'metadata.py' file as a text file.
I've also renamed from _metadata.py to metadata.py to make it cleaner.
added info logging level, we need to move this to a logging.ini

Calling the NApp setup during the NApp init.

Since the `setup()` method works like the `__init__()`, the NApp
developer set some variables to be used on the NApp, expecting them to
be available as soon as the NApp (object) is ready. So, it is much
better to run this setup on the end of the `__init__` method instead of
the `run`.

Start the NApp before setting the listeners.

We need to start the NApp thread before setting the NApp listeners to
effectively start listening to events.

Add rest decorator for REST endpoints

The code, including the decorator, is in APIServer. It mimics Flask
as much as possible by forwarding parameters. This keeps the code small
and the behavior consistent with Flask. Summary:
1. The decorator stores @rest params in function.route_params (same
   strategy as @listen_to);
2. APIServer.start_rest_api(napp) use the bound method and route_params
   exactly like Flask's @app.route does;
3. If a URL and an HTTP method combination is used twice or more, the
   user is warned in the logs and the behavior is the same as Flask's:
   the last declaration prevails.

Deprecate register_rest_endpoint in favor of @rest

Avoid old Kytos dependencies for devs

A common mistake is to run the latest commit of kytos with kytos-utils
and python-openflow from pypi. This leads to invalid bug reports.

Trying to solve this, we install Kytos dependencies from remote
repository. Important changes:
- To have latest kytos _and_ kytos deps:
  1. `git pull`;
  2. `pip install --upgrade -r requirements/dev.txt`;
- To run kytos-utils and python-openflow from a local repo clone,
    install them after installing/upgrading kytos (dev mode).

Replace if .. in with a try .. except.

This is to make the operation atomic, avoiding concurrency errors.

With the list shuffled, it is unlike that two concurrent attempts to get a tag
try the same tag, improving performance. Tests were also update to reflect
the new behavior. Fix #1060.

Test if UNI has tag in as_dict.

As tag is optional in UNI, the method as_dict has to consider the case
where it is None. Now, the key 'user_tag' in the dict is created only
if user_tag attribute exists. Fix #1079.

Consider 'other' can be None in __eq__.

    When testing equality of TAG, consider the case when the 'other' tag is None.

Always return 'tag' key in UNI's as_dict.

The last modification made UNI's as_dict return a dict with
a 'tag' key only if the tag exists. Now, if tag does not exist,
return the key with value None.

Instantiate tag_type when creating a TAG.

Enum TAGType was not being initialized, so any value passed was accepted.
Now only values in TAGType enum are valid.

Change speed property checks

According openflow protocol >= 1.3 spec, "If none of the port speed flags are set, the max_speed or curr_speed are used". So, this commit changes the order of speed checks, checking features_speed before custom_speed.

Create config field in Interface (#1142)

This commit creates a new 'config' field on Interface class. This field can assume one of the following values from Port or PhyPort classes:

OFPPC_PORT_DOWN: Port is administratively down
OFPPC_NO_RECV: Drop all packets received by port
OFPPC_NO_FWD: Drop packets forwarded to port
OFPPC_NO_PACKET_IN: Do not send packet-in messages for port.

Fix #1201: Name collision in Flask Blueprints creation.

Today, the `on_created` method tries to load a NApp that was already
loaded resulting in a name collision in Flask Blueprints creation.
This commit removes the `load_napp` in enable method (`napps/manager.py`).
